Notes from the lecture:¶
  • Standard error of estimate: Average prediction error (Interpretation in relation to the scale of DV)
  • OLS is not iterative vs Maximum Likelihood method which is iterative
  • $R^2:$ How much variation is explained by the predictor?
  • coefficients
    • Unstandardized (b/B): By how many units does the DV increase if the predictor changes by one unit?
    • Standardized ($\beta$): By how many SD does the DV change if the predictor changes by one SD? Intercept = 0. For comparison with other LM.
Notes from books¶
  • Use F-statistic and the associated p-value to answer: Is there a relationship between the p and Y? Because if you have 100 p, 5 will be significant on average (with p>0.05) if you look at the t-statistics. The F-statistic does take the number of p into account.
  • Additive and linear assumption:
    • If $X_1$ increases, then Y increases by $b_1$ units, independent of $X_2, X_3, ...X_i$ (additive assumption) and it does so in a linear way, thus always by one unit for each unit increase in $X_1$ (linear assumption). In reality, it could be that if $X_1$ increases, that the slope $X_2$ changes as a consequence, thereby violating the additive assumption. This is called synergy- or interaction effect!
    • Can be modeled by interaction term (covariate). If you include covariates, then you should keep the main effects in the model, even if they are not significant.
  • Error terms must be uncorrelated
  • Homoscedasticity: Plot fitted values against standardized resdiuals and inspect for patterns such as typical funnel look indicating Homoscedasticity
  • Outlier: Plot studentized residuals: More than 3SD deviation is considered a possible outlier here.
  • Leverage: The leverage statistic $h_i$ is always between 1/n and 1, and the average leverage for all the observations is always equal to (p + 1)/n. We want to watch out for obersations that have more than 2x the average leverage (I indicate that in plots with a dashed line) when I plot leverage vs studentized resdiuals.
  • Multicollinearity: Reduces accuracy of the estimates of regression coefficients
    • The variance inflation factor (VIF) is the ratio of the variance of $\hat\beta_j$ when fitting the full model divided by the variance of $\hat\beta_j$ on its own. The smalles possible VIF is 1. A rule of thumb: VIF>5 or 10 indicates problematic amount of collinearity.
    • If MC is present: Drop problematic variable or combine problematic variable into a single predictor
  • Model accuracy: RSE, $R^2$, better: Cross Validation
  • Model Fit: $MSE = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i - \hat{f}(x_i))^2$
    • Note: This will be only the training MSE here. I will cover e.g. Cross Validation in a separate Notebook or add it here later.
    • Root-MSE more interpretable and therefore more often used
    • Most important is the test MSE, which reflects how well our model reflects the real world.

Influence tests¶

I added the influence scores to the data with the OLSInfluece function. This is necessary for the following plot! Also did I define a cutoff value for Cook's D, which in this case was 0.45 just to illustrate how to mark an outlier visually. According to Cook and Weisberg (1982) values >1 may be cause of concern. Datapoint 404 has high leverage and is clearly an outlier. I plot the model with and without this point below the influence plot.

In [778]:
#Create Influence plot
(ggplot(data, aes(x = 'hat_diag', y = 'student_resid'))
 + geom_point(alpha = 0.3)
 + geom_point(infl, aes(x = 'hat_diag', y = 'student_resid'), color = 'red')
 + geom_text(outlier, aes(label = 'index'), nudge_x = 0.003)
 + geom_vline(xintercept=2*data.hat_diag.mean(), linetype='dashed', alpha=0.4)
 + geom_hline(yintercept=3, alpha=0.4, linetype='dashed')
 + labs(x='Leverage', y='Studentized Residuals'))

Heteroscedasticity¶

The plot above clearly showed Heteroscedasticity. A test to quantify this is Whites Lagrange Multiplier test, the Breush-Pagan test (if the errors are normally distributed, which they are not here) or Goldfeld-Quandt test:

In [781]:
name = ['Lagrange multiplier statistic', 'p-value', 
        'f-value', 'f p-value']
test = sms.het_white(results.resid,results.model.exog)
lzip(name, test)

Model Fit¶

If more than 1% of the absolute values of the standardized residuals are >= 2.5 or more than 5% >= 2, our model might be a poor fit for the data.

In [785]:
p = np.mean(abs(data['standard_resid'])>=2)
pp = np.mean(abs(data['standard_resid'])>=2.5)
print('{:.3f}% 2.0 SD \n{:.3f}% 2.5 SD'.format(p*100,pp*100))

4.516% 2.0 SD 
3.656% 2.5 SD
